{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} {{Multiple issues |{{Notability|Products|date=December 2008}} {{primary sources|date=September 2008}} }} {{Infobox Magazine | title = Christian Order | editor = Rod Pead | editor_title = Editor | previous_editor = Fr Paul Crane SJ | frequency = monthly | category = Conservative Catholicism | firstdate = 1960 | country = UK | based = UK | language = English | website = http://www.christianorder.com/ | issn = 0009-5559 }}
'''''Christian Order''''' is a British-based monthly magazine for [[Traditionalist Catholic]]s<ref>[http://www.christianorder.com/index.html ''Christian Order''] official website</ref> which was described by John Beaumont of ''Fidelity'' magazine in 1996 as "most influential of the conservative Catholic journals in the United Kingdom".<ref>[http://sspx.agenda.tripod.com/id23.html "The Vanishing Schism Revisited"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514061547/http://sspx.agenda.tripod.com/id23.html |date=14 May 2008 }}, by John Beaumont, ''Fidelity'' magazine, November 1996</ref>
It was originally devoted to the Catholic response to social issues, taking a [[distributist]] stance sceptical of the [[welfare state]].<ref>[http://tcbh.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/9/1/86 "Faith and Community Threatened? Roman Catholic Responses to the Welfare State, Materialism and Social Mobility, 1945–62"] by Joan Keating, ''Twentieth Century History'', Volume 9, Number 1, Oxford University Press</ref> In the 1970s a number of contributors were attracted such as George Telford (former vice-chairman and Secretary to the Catechetical Commission of the Bishops of England and Wales)<ref>[http://www.angelusonline.org/print.php?sid=2976 "The Kingship of Christ Since Vatican II"]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, by Michael Davies, ''[[The Angelus (magazine)|The Angelus]]''</ref> and the lay author [[Michael Davies (Catholic writer)|Michael Davies]].<ref>[http://www.ifuv.org/docs/michaeldavies_01.html Michael Davies obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717132655/http://www.ifuv.org/docs/michaeldavies_01.html |date=17 July 2010 }}, Leo Darroch, 27 April 2005, Mass of Ages, hosted on the website of [[Una Voce]]</ref>
The magazine's rationale is presented in confrontational terms: {{quote|Unless the Church is militant, She cannot thrive and flourish. Thus Christian Order is a militant antidote to the secular "live and let live" attitude which has brought the Church low. For forty years it has embodied that uncompromising spirit demanded by [[Pope Leo XIII]], who contended that in times of necessity each Catholic is "under obligation to show forth his faith to instruct and encourage other of the Faithful" (Sapientiae Christianae).<ref>[http://www.christianorder.com/about.html About Us], Christian Order</ref>}}
The [[Neocatechumenal Way]] is criticized in the magazine as "heretical" ([[Lutheran]]) and a "Trojan horse" in the Church.<ref> {{cite journal | url= http://www.christianorder.com/features/features_2002/features_oct02.html |title= The Last Trojan Horse? | author=Michael McGrade | work = Christian Order | date=October 2002 |accessdate=8 September 2008}} </ref> In an article published in the magazine, CJ O'Hehir described Ireland as "the most anti-Catholic Catholic country in the world, and the most monolithically liberal of the world's democracies."<ref>[https://archive.today/20070812032258/http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2005/11/13/story9624.asp "All on the anti-Church bandwagon"], by Kieron Wood, [[The Sunday Business Post]], 13 November 2005</ref> The magazine has republished articles from ''Daylight,'' the magazine of the Catholic creationist [[Daylight Origins Society]].<ref> {{cite journal | url= http://www.christianorder.com/features/features_1998/features_aug-sep98.html |title = Theistic Evolution and the Mystery of FAITH |author= Anthony Nevard | work = Christian Order | date=August–September 1998 |accessdate=8 September 2008}} </ref><ref> {{cite journal | url= http://www.christianorder.com/editorials/editorials_2006/editorials_jan06.html | title = Editorial: Evolving Into Atheism | work = Christian Order | date=January 2006 | accessdate=8 September 2008}} </ref>
It has been criticised by ''[[Searchlight (magazine)|Searchlight]]'' magazine for having among its contributors "extremists" (including [[John Vennari]]), a "race-baiter" ([[E. Michael Jones]]) and an "antisemitic conspiracist" ([[Robert Sungenis]]),<ref>[http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/index.php?link=template&story=16 Faith-based fascists bridging the waters], ''[[Searchlight (magazine)|Searchlight]]'' magazine, Mike Reynolds, March 2004</ref> and the website ''Catholic Culture'' suggests that its contents should be looked at in "a critical light" due to "a bias against Church leaders, [[Vatican II]], and the [[Novus Ordo Mass|New Mass]]."<ref>[http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/reviews/view.cfm?recnum=1665 Catholic Culture :Site review: ''Christian Order'']</ref>
