'''Marshall Jerome Gauvin''' (April 3, 1881 – September 23, 1978), best known as '''Marshall J. Gauvin''' was a Canadian [[Atheism|atheist]] author and speaker in the [[freethought]] movement.
Gauvin was born near [[Moncton, New Brunswick]].<ref>[http://umanitoba.ca/libraries/units/archives/collections/rad/gauvin.html "Marshall Gauvin fonds"]. University of Manitoba.</ref> He was a contributor to the ''[[Truth Seeker]]'', a publication devoted to freethought.<ref name="Truth Seeker Journal">{{cite web|url=http://www.truthseeker.com/truth-seeker/|title=Truth Seeker Journal|accessdate=17 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205231638/http://www.truthseeker.com/truth-seeker/|archivedate=2007-02-05}}</ref>
His collected writings are part of the collection of the [[University of Manitoba]].<ref name="Archives">{{cite web|url=http://www.umanitoba.ca/libraries/units/archives/collections/complete_holdings/ead/html/gauvin.shtml|title=Marshall J. Gauvin: An Inventory of His Papers |work=[[University of Manitoba Archives & Special Collections]]|year=2011|publisher=University of Manitoba|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://umanitoba.ca/libraries/units/archives/collections/complete_holdings/rad/mss/gauvin.shtml|title=Marshall Gauvin fonds, 1881-|year=1998|work= University of Manitoba Archives & Special Collections|publisher=University of Manitoba Libraries|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref> The description of the collection at the '''Directory of Special Collections of Research Value in Canadian Libraries''' states that "The collection is noted for its comprehensive holdings in free thought and rationalist literature." and " ...there is substantial material on atheism, biblical studies, science, oratory, early women's studies, and English literature and history."[http://www.collectioncanada.ca/collectionsp-bin/colldisp/l=0/c=202]
