'''Shmuel Szteinhendler''', a [[rabbi]] in [[Santiago, Chile]], is considered the current [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Cuba]] as well as the regional director for [[Masorti Olami]] in [[Latin America]].<ref>[http://www.masortiworld.org/news/monthly-report/12-05/update-activities.htm Rabbis of Chilean Masorti Forum meet with Mr. Zeev Bielsky] Masorti World {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820020338/http://www.masortiworld.org/news/monthly-report/12-05/update-activities.htm |date=August 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/Cuba.html The Virtual Jewish History Tour Cuba] Jewish Virtual Library</ref><ref>[http://www.hadassah.org/news/content/per_hadassah/archive/2005/05_JAN/traveler.asp The Jewish Traveler: Havana] Hadassah Magazine{{Dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>
Szteinhendler was born in [[Argentina]] and trained as a [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]] rabbi in [[Buenos Aires]].<ref name="jo">Ozzie Nogg, [http://www.jewishomaha.org/page.aspx?id=119280 A Visit to Jewish Cuba: It’s Impossible to Come Back Unchanged] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002012918/http://www.jewishomaha.org/page.aspx?id=119280 |date=2011-10-02 }}, Jewish Press, The Jewish Federation of Omaha. Accessed August 15, 2011</ref> He started visiting Cuba regularly since 1992, operating from his base in Guadalajara, Mexico, and oversaw a revival of the Jewish culture there, serving as an informal spiritual head of the Jewish community in Cuba.<ref>Jerry Berke, [http://www.jewishfederations.org/page.aspx?id=600 Havana Synagogue Dark for Decades is Once Again Aglow in the Light of Shabbat Candles] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812015808/http://www.jewishfederations.org/page.aspx?id=600 |date=2011-08-12 }}, The Jewish Federations of North America. Accessed August 15, 2011</ref><ref>Dana Evan Kaplan, [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0411/is_2_49/ai_64332275/pg_5/ A Jewish Renaissance in Castro's Cuba], ''Judaism'', Spring 2000. Accessed August 15, 2011</ref><ref name="jc">Kenneth Bandler, [http://www.jewishcuba.org/bandler3.html Argentine rabbi ignites fervor in dormant Cuban communities], The Jews of Cuba, 1996. Accessed August 15, 2011</ref> Szteinhendler's visits to Cuba were sponsored by the [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]].<ref name="jc"/><ref>Ruth Behar, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZKrMxwecYlgC&pg=PA179&dq=%22Shmuel+Szteinhendler%22&hl=en&ei=b-pGTpayGq-LsALxtKWSCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Shmuel%20Szteinhendler%22&f=false An island called home: returning to Jewish Cuba], New Brunswick, N.J., Rutgers University Press, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-8135-4189-1}}; p. 179</ref>
